snippet.textDisplay:
some comments:

1. criticism & cynicism among artists are not based on gender, both male & female got it

2. people don't explain ways of success of artists based on gender... success is due to hard work, creativity, timing, and luck... that goes for both genders

3. detractors / haters always hate, that happens to any artists, it's good that taylor takes that as fuel for creativity

4. backlash & critics is always there, that's just the way the industry is... it's not only to woman in music... it's to all genders in all industries

5. be song writer, perfecting voice, enhancing stamina during tour, it's all the recipe for success for musicians whether it's male or female

6. nobody cares that much about your dating life, the entertainment media and tabloid might care, but much more people care about your music, about what you're producing

7. too many breakup songs in an album, etc, is part of the feedback, it's your choice to adjust the next album based on the previous feedback, it's a very normal process in your creativity, it's just like listening to the market demand... it's nothing to complain about

8. again critics about artists romantic life, fashion, & body happens to all genders

9. 'i really like his song but something about him i don't like'... yes i've heard that before for many male artists

10. agree with your statement, the only way forward is forward motion... that is recipe for both gender artists

11. who's holding woman... i think in all industries appreciates more competence instead of the genders

12. nothing is wrong with scooter braun buying your catalog, that's how the market is working. just like michael jackson buying beatles catalog. if you want to buy back your catalog then go ahead do the negotiation with scooter, it's all about numbers, not about feeling. this is how market is working, nothing to do with male privilege.

13. rights to own music depends on the contract & negotiations. what did you sign with your labels ? didn't you receive some amount of money during the contract signing ? unless at that time you didn't sign anything with anybody, when somebody claims your catalog then that would be a crime... or perhaps long time ago your lawyer daddy didn't do a proper due diligence during the signing ?

snippet.textDisplay:
I love how she shows her writing talent not only in her songs, but also in her speeches - how she managed to cleverly weave in "like ever" and "happy, free, confused and lonely" as an easter egg to us fans while still talking about such weighty concepts as gender equality and regulating private equity in music.
This vision and talent is why she's the woman of the decade.

snippet.textDisplay:
Taylor winning Woman of the Decade and her speech right now...is helping me understand the mentality of this generation (why so many people supported her). Also she is revealing a lot about what struggle and empowerment meant to her (particularly when I realised she had issue with not being given FULL credit for her work -- she's not happy people say it's because of her label or her co-writers or her controversies in her private life. It is much more meaningful for her to be credited fully as an INDIVIDUAL. I didn't grow up in America, so that's interesting to see.

I also think that Taylor is not only a "Woman in Music," but a "Woman in Pop." She is very much visually and physically represented. I hope that in the near future, maybe Billboard can include female songwriters, producers in the nomination / consideration of their Women of the Year/Decade award.

Even though I am still in my 20s, I find myself a bit alienated from the times and my generation. I learned a lot from this video, especially with regards to what people find meaningful, purposeful, or called to do in their journey called "LIFE."
